definition: "Cystatin C is a low-molecular-weight protein produced at a constant rate by all nucleated cells in the body. Because it is produced at a steady rate independent of muscle mass, sex, or diet, and is freely filtered by the kidneys and almost entirely reabsorbed and degraded in the proximal tubule, its serum concentration is determined almost exclusively by the glomerular filtration rate (GFR). This makes it a more accurate and less biased measure of kidney filtration function than creatinine, which is significantly influenced by muscle mass, protein intake, and age. Cystatin C also has independent biological activity as an inhibitor of cysteine proteases, and elevated circulating cystatin C may reflect tissue catabolism and inflammation beyond its kidney filtration role."
why_it_matters: "Cystatin C is more sensitive than creatinine for detecting early-stage kidney function decline, and it predicts cardiovascular mortality and all-cause mortality more powerfully than creatinine-based eGFR in population studies. The critical limitation of creatinine is its strong dependence on muscle mass: a muscular young man and a frail elderly woman with identical creatinine levels have vastly different kidney function. Cystatin C eliminates this confound. In older adults and people with reduced muscle mass — exactly the populations where kidney function decline matters most — cystatin C reveals impaired GFR that creatinine misses entirely. Multiple prospective studies have found that individuals misclassified as having normal kidney function by creatinine but impaired function by cystatin C have cardiovascular and mortality risk comparable to those with confirmed kidney disease."

